		<h1>About All of this</h1>

		<hr />

    	<h2>The Story</h2>
    	<p><em>A Tale of Thorns</em> is an epic, ongoing fantasy serial about identity, rebellion, memory, sacrifice, and love across lifetimes. It's a story where goddesses may walk among mortals, the past is never truly gone, and the cycle of tragedy might finally be broken &ndash; if the people would get out of their own damned way.</p>
    
    	<p>The series follows Rose &ndash; a storyteller &ndash; who inhabits souls across the many worlds she envisioned throughout her life, only starting as she met her own end:</p>
    	<ul>
			<li>
				<em>Of Leafs and Thorns</em> (Arc 1): A world in which the goddesses are believed long dead, save the one goddess propped up by the state religion, a single family must navigate their past and find a way to change the world for the better.
				<ul>
    			    <li><em>The Blue and Silver Rose</em> (Book 1): Roisin, a young woman from a rural district, survives a monstrous attack and is saved by Jasmin, a noblewoman with a guilty past. Together, they flee a tyrannical queen, uncover forgotten memories, and discover they are the reincarnations of a legendary warrior and a fallen goddess. Their love story unfolds against a backdrop of rebellion, divine conspiracy, and a final, costly confrontation with a creature known as the Fiend.</li>
		        	<li><em>The Tower of Snow and Wind</em> (Book 2): Five hundred years earlier, Nyxara, a reluctant baker plagued by dreams of a forgotten goddess, journeys to a sacred mountain temple. She rejects a pre-ordained destiny, choosing instead to define her own path. Alongside the grieving Micah, she uncovers the tragic origin of the Fiend &ndash; a corrupted soul from the past &ndash; and fights to bind the ancient evil, setting the stage for Roisin's time.</li>
	        		<li><em>The Heroine, Haunted and Holy</em> (Book 3): Delia, Roisin's sister, awakens with no memory in the capital. As she pieces together her identity with the help of divine allies, she witnesses Roisin's death and nearly unmakes reality itself in her grief. Her choice to accept comfort instead of destruction finally breaks the endless cycle, leading to a new era of rebuilding, forgiveness, and unexpected hope.</li>
				</ul>
			</li><!--
