		<p>More to be added as the story unfolds.</p>

	    <p>This project was officially started in 2024 from a simple shower thought: <em>what if every world you ever imagined becomes a reality for you to explore in your afterlife?</em> It quickly grew into an epic spanning thousands of years, multiple worlds.</p>
		<p>I'm publishing this as an online serial &ndash; the old human standby used and abused by the greats and the not-so-greats &ndash; because this story is too big and too personal to tell any other way.</p>

		<hr />

		<h2>Release Schedule</h2>
		<p>New chapters post on the <strong>5th, 10th, 15th, 20th, 25th, and last</strong> day of each month. Each chapter typically runs 1500-5000 words, and with limited exceptions chapters come with built-in stopping points.</p>
		<p>Book 3 is currently in progress. Book 4 will pick up immediately upon completion.</p>
		<!-- <p>You can subscribe via <strong>[RSS / newsletter / social media link]</strong> to get updates when new chapters go live.</p> -->

		<hr />

		<h2>About Me</h2>
    	<p>My name is Terra Macdonald. I'm a sapphic trans woman from a tiny town in East Texas, now living in Colorado with my wife Katie, and a small zoo of pets (Cinder the chaos cat, Zeus the sweet dog, Beans the skittish tuxy, Peanut the spicy hognose, Nessie the long gorl corn snake, and Egg the hermit crab survivor).</p>
    
    	<p>I've written under various names over the years, including Vicious Elia Rayne (art, essays, educational videos), Tommy Harris (short stories, poetry, abandoned novels), and Terra Branford (essays). My professional background is in mathematics (M.Sc. in Mathematics with an Applied Mathematics focus) and computer science &ndash; I'm self-taught in C/C++, Python, PHP, and more, and I built this site myself.</p>
    
    	<p>Why include all this? Because every part of who I am matters to how I write. Being trans means I write about identity and transformation with a certain urgency. Being sapphic means the love stories in these pages are queer, joyful, and unapologetic. Being a mathematician means I love systems, cycles, and patterns &ndash; and then breaking them. Being a parent means I write about sacrifice, hope, and the future I want my daughter to inherit.</p>
    
    	<p>I believe in education, visibility, and social awareness. I use every opportunity I have to help people learn what they need to know &ndash; whether that's through code, story, or just showing up as my authentic self. If you're young and scared and need to know it gets better: it does. I'm proof.</p>
    
    	<p>Later, I'll add pictures and more details. For now, this is enough.</p>
    
	    <hr />

		<h2>Content Warnings & Reading Notes</h2>
    	<p>
			<em>A Tale of Thorns</em> deals with mature themes including: violence, death, torture, psychological trauma, systemic oppression, dysphoria, and grief. The books also contain explicit romantic content between consenting adults (primarily f/f relationships). Please be aware this is not YA fiction.
		</p>
		<p>
			Each book of A Tale of Thorns may be taken as a standalone story, but they are best read in the order presented in <a href="/archive">the archive</a>. Each arc is explicitly standalone, though the specifics of Rose's journey are interwoven throughout as prologues, epilogues, and other narrative elements. While the arcs can be read in any order, there are some elements that are recurring devices across arcs, and the subtlety &ndash; or lack thereof in many cases &ndash; of these details is better appreciated when read in order.
		</p>
		<p>
			The story is set in a complex fantasy world with many sub-settings that range from realism to sci-fi to experimental. Most of the story is written in first-person, though some is third-person omniscient or third-person close. Each portion of the story is written to match the particular perspective of Rose's incarnation in that book with the exception of (spoilers) in <a href="/archive#the-tower-of-snow-and-wind">The Tower of Snow and Wind</a>, <a href="/archive#the-heroine-haunted-and-holy">The Heroine, Haunted and Holy</a>, and maybe some others in later books. The sudden shifts in perspective may be jarring.
		</p>
		<p>
			I do not have an editor on staff. I do not have a proofreader on staff. I do not have a sensitivity reader on staff. I do not have a beta reader on staff. I am the only person who has read any of the story before it is published. I am the only person who has read any of the story after it is published. I am the only person who has read any of the story at all. If you find typos, plot holes, or other issues, please let me know! I will try to fix them as soon as possible. That said ...
		</p>
		<p>
			There are some places where the story has explicitly inaccessible features as part of the narrative. This is often intentional, and in those places, I include notes explaining the inaccessibility. In all cases, I would rather break immersion than exclude disabled readers, so if you find something that is inaccessible and does not have a note, or if you find an inaccessible feature that might have been unintentional, please let me know! I will try to fix it as soon as possible.
		</p>
		<p>
			Finally. I do all the art, all the writing, all the coding and maintenance, all the graphic design. EVERYTHING. This means:
			<ol> 
				<li> lower quality art than professional stuff or comics, </li>
				<li> slower updates when art is involved, </li>
				<li> slower updates when (spoiler) happens in Books 3, 4, 5, and possibly others in the future, and </li>
				<li> a lot of flaws. </li>
			</ol>
			So please be patient with me.</p>
		<p>
			I'm not willing to use LLMs to help with any part of this. If you want to help, sharing with friends who will like the story is a good start. If you want to help more, this project will eventually be up on <a href="https://github.com/ViciousElia">GitHub</a>, though none of the narrative will be available there. I also have a <a href="https://ko-fi.com/viciouselia">ko-fi page</a> if you're interested in supporting financially. A Tale of Thorns is and always will be free to read, so you should never feel obligated.
		</p>
